contextHelp.alternate: Whether or not the injectors should be fired at the same time. This setting is ignored when Sequential is selected below, however it will still affect the req_fuel value.
contextHelp.engineType: Engines with an equal number of degrees between all firings (This is most engines) should select Even fire. Some 2 and 6 cylinder engines are Odd fire however.
contextHelp.mapSample: The method used for calculating the MAP reading\nFor 1-2 Cylinder engines, Cycle Minimum is recommended.\nFor more than 2 cylinders Cycle Average is recommended
contextHelp.mapSwitchPoint: Below this RPM instantaneous map sample method is used, instead of selected one.\nSet 0 RPM to disable (Default)
contextHelp.stoich: The stoichiometric ration of the fuel being used. For flex fuel, choose the primary fuel
contextHelp.injLayout:
The injector layout and timing to be used. Options are: 
 1. Paired - 2 injectors per output. Outputs active is equal to half the number of cylinders. Outputs are timed over 1 crank revolution. 
 2. Semi-sequential: Same as paired except that injector channels are mirrored (1&4, 2&3) meaning the number of outputs used are equal to the number of cylinders. Only valid for 4 cylinders or less. 
 3. Banked: 2 outputs only used. 
 4. Sequential: 1 injector per output and outputs used equals the number of cylinders. Injection is timed over full cycle.
contextHelp.inj4CylPairing: Which outputs will be paired when semi-sequential fuel injection is used (4 cylinder engines). Pairing depends on firing order
contextHelp.TrigPattern: The type of input trigger decoder to be used.
contextHelp.useResync: If enabled, sync will be rechecked once every full cycle from the cam input. This is good for accuracy, however if your cam input is noisy then this can cause issues.
contextHelp.trigPatternSec: Cam mode/type also known as Secondary Trigger Pattern.
contextHelp.PollLevelPol: The level of the cam trigger input will be checked at tooth #1 and this defines if the level is supposed to be High or Low at 1st phase of the engine.
contextHelp.numTeeth: Number of teeth on Primary Wheel.
contextHelp.missingTeeth: Number of Missing teeth on Primary Wheel.
contextHelp.TrigAng: The Angle ATDC when tooth No:1 on the primary wheel passes the primary sensor. The range of this field is -360 to +360 degrees.
contextHelp.TrigAngMul: A multiplier used by non-360 degree tooth wheels (i.e. Wheels where the tooth count doesn't divide evenly into 360. Usage: (360 * <multiplier>) / tooth_count = Whole number
contextHelp.SkipCycles: The number of revolutions that will be skipped during cranking before the injectors and coils are fired.
contextHelp.TrigEdge: The Trigger edge of the primary sensor.\nLeading.\nTrailing.
contextHelp.TrigEdgeSec: The Trigger edge of the secondary (Cam) sensor.\nLeading.\nTrailing.
contextHelp.TrigFilter: Tuning of the trigger filter algorithm. The more aggressive the setting, the more noise will be removed, however this increases the chance of some true readings being filtered out (False positive). Medium is safe for most setups. Only select 'Aggressive' if no other options are working
contextHelp.sparkMode: Wasted Spark: Ignition outputs are on the channels <= half the number of cylinders. Eg 4 cylinder outputs on IGN1 and IGN2.\nSingle Channel: All ignition pulses are output on IGN1.\nWasted COP: Ignition pulses are output on all ignition channels up to the number of cylinders. Eg 4 cylinder outputs on all ignition channels. Note that your board needs to have same number of igntion outputs as cylinders to be able to run this
contextHelp.IgInv: Whether the spark fires when the ignition signal goes high or goes low. Nearly all ignition systems use 'Going Low' but please verify this as damage to coils can result from the incorrect selection. (NOTE: THIS IS NOT MEGASQUIRT. THIS SETTING IS USUALLY THE OPPOSITE OF WHAT THEY USE!)
contextHelp.sparkDur: The duration of the spark at full dwell. Typically around 1ms
contextHelp.fixAngEnable: If enabled, timing will be locked/fixed and the ignition map will be ignored. Note that this value will be overridden by the fixed cranking value when cranking
contextHelp.FixAng: Timing will be locked at this value if the above is enabled
contextHelp.crankRPM: The cranking RPM threshold. When RPM is lower than this value (and above 0) the system will be considered to be cranking
contextHelp.tpsflood: Keep throttle over this value to disable the priming pulse and cranking fuel. Used to prevent flood or clear already flooded engine
contextHelp.fanHyster: The number of degrees of hysteresis to be used in controlling the fan. Recommended values are between 2 and 5
contextHelp.fanWhenCranking: Whether the fan should be disabled or continue running when the engine is cranking
contextHelp.fanWhenOff: Whether the fan will continue to run when the engine is turned off
contextHelp.fanPin: The Arduino pin that the fan control signal will output on. This is NOT necessarily the same as the connector pin on any particular board
contextHelp.fanSP: The trigger temperature for the fan. Fan will be enabled above this temp
contextHelp.vssPulsesPerKm: The number of pulses on the VSS signal per KM/Mile
contextHelp.vssSmoothing: A smoothing factor to help reduce noise in the VSS signal. Typical values are between 0 and 50
contextHelp.aeTime: The duration of the acceleration enrichment
contextHelp.iacChannels: The number of output channels used for PWM valves. Select 1 for 2-wire valves or 2 for 3-wire valves.
contextHelp.iacStepTime: Duration of each stepping pulse. Values that are too low can cause the motor to behave erratically or not at all. See the manual for suggested step times
contextHelp.iacCoolTime: Cool time between each step. Set to zero if you don't want any cooling at all
contextHelp.iacStepHome: Homing steps to perform on startup. Must be greater than the fully open steps value
contextHelp.iacMaxSteps: Maximum number of steps the IAC can be moved away from the home position. Should always be less than Homing steps.
contextHelp.iacStepHyster: The minimum number of steps to move in any one go.
contextHelp.iacAlgorithm:
Selects method of idle control.
None = no idle control valve.
On/Off valve.
PWM valve (2,3 wire).
Stepper Valve (4,6,8 wire).
contextHelp.iacPWMdir: Normal PWM valves increase RPM with higher duty. If RPM decreases with higher duty then select Reverse
contextHelp.iacPWMrun: Determines if the idle valve runs before engine is cranked over. This can help starting the engine by letting more air in before the RPM sync is achieved.
contextHelp.iacCLminDuty: When using closed loop idle control, this is the minimum duty cycle that the PID loop will allow. Combined with the maximum value, this specifies the working range of your idle valve
contextHelp.iacCLmaxDuty: When using closed loop idle control, this is the maximum duty cycle that the PID loop will allow. Combined with the minimum value, this specifies the working range of your idle valve
contextHelp.iacTPSlimit: When using OL+CL idle control, if the TPS is higher than this value closed loop idle resets the integral of the PID (To prevent RPM dips coming back to idle)
contextHelp.iacRPMlimitHysteresis: When using closed loop idle control, if the closed loop Target RPM + this value is higher than the actual RPM, closed loop idle resets the integral of the PID (To prevent RPM dips coming back to idle)
contextHelp.iacFastTemp: Below this temperature, the idle output will be high (On). Above this temperature, it will turn off.
contextHelp.idleUpPolarity: Normal polarity is a ground switch where an earthed signal activates the Idle Up. The internal pullup will be enabled with Normal polarity. \n Inverted may be used if a 5v signal is used to enable the Idle Up.
contextHelp.CTPSPolarity: Normal polarity is a ground switch where an earthed signal activates the closed throttle position. The internal pullup will be enabled with Normal polarity. \n Inverted may be used if a 5v signal is used to enable the closed throttle position.
contextHelp.idleUpAdder: The amount (In either Duty Cycle % or Steps (Depending on the idle control method in use), that the idle control will increase by when Idle Up is active
contextHelp.idleAdvEnabled: Added setting adds curve values to current spark table values when user defined idle is active. \n Switched setting overrides spark table values and uses curve values for idle ignition timing.
contextHelp.idleAdvAlgorithm: Use Throttle position sensor (TPS) or closed throttle position sensor (CTPS) to detect idle state.
contextHelp.idleAdvDelay: The number of seconds after sync is achieved before the idle advance control begins
contextHelp.idleAdvStartDelay: The number of seconds after matching settings before the idle advance control begins
contextHelp.idleTaperTime: Soft time transition from crank to running PWM targets
contextHelp.oddfire2: The ATDC angle of channel 2 for oddfire engines. This is relative to the TDC angle of channel 1
contextHelp.oddfire3: The ATDC angle of channel 3 for oddfire engines. This is relative to the TDC angle of channel 1 (NOT channel 2)
contextHelp.oddfire4: The ATDC angle of channel 4 for oddfire engines. This is relative to the TDC angle of channel 1 (NOT channel 3)
contextHelp.aeColdPct: Acceleration enrichment adjustment for cold engine. Cold adjustment % is tapered between start and end temperatures.\n100% = no adjustment.
contextHelp.aeColdTaperMin: AE cold adjustment taper start temperature. When coolant is below this value, full cold adjustment is applied.
contextHelp.aeColdTaperMax: AE cold adjustment taper end temperature. When coolant is above this value, no cold adjustment is applied.
contextHelp.dfcoRPM: The RPM above which DFCO will be active. Typically set a few hundred RPM above maximum idle speed
contextHelp.dfcoHyster: Hysteresis for DFCO RPM. 200-300 RPM is typical for this, however a higher value may be needed if the RPM is fluctuating around the cutout speed
contextHelp.dfcoTPSThresh: The TPS value below which DFCO will be active. Typical value is 5%-10%, but higher may be needed if TPS signal is noisy
contextHelp.launchPin: The ARDUINO pin that the clutch switch is connected to. This is NOT the pin on the connector, but the pin it relates to on the arduino
contextHelp.launchHiLo: Whether the signal is High or Low when the clutch pedal is engaged. For a ground switching input (Most clutch switches), this should be LOW
contextHelp.lnchPullRes: Whether the internal pullup resistor is enabled or left floating. For a ground switching input (Most clutch switches), select Pullup. For a 0v-5v input, select Floating
contextHelp.ignBypassPin: The ARDUINO pin that the ignition bypass is connected to. This is NOT the pin on the connector, but the pin it relates to on the arduino
contextHelp.ignBypassEnable: If turned on, a ground signal will be output during cranking on the specified pin. This is used to bypass the Speeduino ignition control during cranking.
contextHelp.ignCranklock: On certain low resolution ignition patterns, the cranking timing can be locked to occur when a pulse is received.
contextHelp.multiplyMAP: If enabled, the MAP reading is included directly into the pulsewidth calculation by multiplying the VE lookup value by either the MAP:Baro ratio or MAP/100.\n This results in a flatter VE table that can be easier to tune in some instances. The MAP/100 option is generally used for compatibility with fuel tables from other ECUs. MAP:Baro ratio is recommended for new tunes. \n VE table must be retuned when this value is changed.
contextHelp.legacyMAP: Use the legacy method of reading the MAP sensor that was used prior to the 201905 firmware. This should ONLY be enabled if you are upgrading from a firmware earlier than this
contextHelp.includeAFR: When enabled, the current AFR reading is incorporated directly in the pulsewidth calculation as a percentage of the current target ratio. VE table must be retuned when this value is changed.
contextHelp.incorporateAFR: When enabled, the AFR stoich/AFR target -ratio is incorporated directly in the pulsewidth calculation. When enabled, AFR target table affects pulsewidth even with EGO disabled. VE table must be retuned when this value is changed.
contextHelp.useExtBaro: By Default, Speeduino will measure barometric pressure upon startup. Optionally however, a 2nd pressure sensor can be used to perform live barometric readings whilst the system is on.
contextHelp.flexEnabled: Turns on readings from the Flex sensor and enables the below adjustments
contextHelp.flexFreqLow: The frequency of the sensor at 0% ethanol (50Hz for standard GM/Continental sensor)
contextHelp.flexFreqHigh: The frequency of the sensor at 100% ethanol (150Hz for standard GM/Continental sensor)
contextHelp.flexFuelAdj: Fuel % to be used for the current ethanol % (Typically 100% @ 0%, 163% @ 100%)
contextHelp.flexAdvAdj: Additional advance (in degrees) for the current ethanol % (Typically 0 @ 0%, 10-20 @ 100%)
contextHelp.flexBoostAdj: Adjustment, in kPa, to the boost target for the current ethanol %. Negative values are allowed to lower boost at lower ethanol % if necessary.
contextHelp.n2o_arming_pin: Pin that the nitrous arming/engagement switch is on.
contextHelp.n2o_pin_polarity: Whether Nitrous is active (Armed) when the pin is LOW or HIGH. If LOW is selected, the internal pullup will be used.
contextHelp.flatSArm: The RPM switch point that determines whether an engaged clutch is for launch control or flat shift. Below this figure, an engaged clutch is considered to be for launch, above this figure an active clutch input will be considered a flat shift. This should be set at least several hundred RPM above idle
contextHelp.flatSSoftWin: The number of RPM below the flat shift point where the softlimit will be applied (aka Soft limit window). Recommended values are 200-1000
contextHelp.flatSRetard: The absolute timing (BTDC) that will be used when within the soft limit window
contextHelp.engineProtectType: Whether the engine protect an rev limiter will cut the fuel, the ignition or both
contextHelp.hardCutType: How hard cuts should be performed for rev/launch limits. Full cut will stop all ignition events, Rolling cut will step through all ignition outputs, only cutting 1 per revolution
contextHelp.SoftLimitMode: Fixed: the soft limiter will retard the ignition advance to the specified value.\nRelative: current timing advance will be retarted by the specified amount
contextHelp.hardRevLim: A fixed hard rev limit is a single point that the fuel or ignition (or both) will be cut completely to reduce increasing RPMs
contextHelp.engineProtectMaxRPM: The RPM point that engine protections will engage from. Below this RPM value, engine protections will NOT be active
contextHelp.afrProtectMAP: Minimum manifold air pressure the AFR lean protection will activate
contextHelp.afrProtectRPM: Minimum RPM the AFR lean protection will activate
contextHelp.afrProtectTPS: Minimum current throttle position for the AFR lean protection to activate
contextHelp.afrProtectDeviation: Fixed mode = A fixed maximum AFR value (e.g. 14.0)\n\nTable mode = A maximum deviation (e.g. 1.5) from current AFR using target table + specified deviation
contextHelp.afrProtectCutTime: Time delay before activating AFR protection when all conditions has been fulfilled
contextHelp.afrProtectReactivationTPS: Going below this throttle position (%) will deactivate this protection
contextHelp.fuel2InputPin: The Arduino pin that is being used to trigger the second fuel table to be active
contextHelp.fuel2InputPolarity: Whether the 2nd fuel table should be active when input is high or low. This should be LOW for a typical ground switching input
contextHelp.fuel2InputPullup: Whether to use the built in PULLUP for the switching input. This should be Yes for a typical ground switching input
contextHelp.enable_secondarySerial: This Enables the secondary serial port . Secondary serial is serial3 on mega2560 processor, and Serial2 on STM32 and Teensy processor
contextHelp.cltAdvValues: This curve can be used to advance ignition timing when engine is warming up. This can also be used to warm up the catalytic converters in cold start by retarding timing. Or even as safety feature to retard timing when engine is too hot to prevent knock.
contextHelp.fpPrime: Duration to power fuel pump on to ensure fuel line pressure.
contextHelp.primingDelay: Delay to priming after fuel pump is on, used to wait fuel line get pressurised correctly.
contextHelp.idleUpOutputEnabled: Enable an output that is toggled by the idle up input pin. An example use is driving an AC fan relay.
contextHelp.idleUpOutputInv: No = When the idle up pin is high the output is active (grounding), when the idle up pin is low the output is inactive. Yes = When the idle up pin is high the output is inactive, when the idle up pin is low the output is active (grounding).
contextHelp.crankingEnrichTaper: Taper time from cranking enrichment to ASE or run (after engine has started).
contextHelp.lnchCtrlTPS: The minimum TPS percentage that launch control will engage at
contextHelp.lnchSoftLim: The RPM point that the launch control ignition timing adjustment will engage (When under launch conditions). Should be below the hard rev limit RPM
contextHelp.lnchRetard: When under launch conditions (Eg Clutch engaged) the ignition timing will be set to this when above the Soft rev limit. This will override any other ignition modifiers
contextHelp.lnchHardLim: The RPM point above which the fuel and/or ignition will be cut when launch is active (Eg Clutch engaged). See the Engine Protection dialog to set whether it is fuel, ignition or both that are cut.
contextHelp.lnchFuelAdd: The additional fuel % that will be added during Soft and Hard launch conditions. Set to 0 for no fuel modifier.
contextHelp.true_address: This is the 11bit Can address of the Speeduino ECU
contextHelp.realtime_base_address: This is the 11bit CAN address of the realtime data broadcast from the Speeduino ECU. This MUST be at least 0x16 greater than the true address

contextHelp.ADCFILTER_MAP: This setting is only available when using the Instantaneous MAP sampling method. Recommended value: 20
contextHelp.ADCFILTER_BARO: This setting is only available when using an external Baro sensor. Recommended value: 64
contextHelp.FILTER_FLEX: Higher values provide more filtering, but slower Eth% and fuel temp response. Recommended value: 75
contextHelp.boostIntv: The closed loop control interval will run every this many ms. Generally values between 50% and 100% of the valve frequency work best
contextHelp.boostByGearEnabled: Open loop -> Constant limit in Duty cycle %\nClosed Loop -> Constant limit in kPa\nIn both cases the multiplied option simply takes a percentage of the values in the boost table
contextHelp.vvtMode:
Selects method of VVT control.
On/Off = No PWM control and output is only on or off.
Open Loop = PWM control where duty is taken directly from VVT table.
Closed Loop = PWM control where VVT table is Cam angle target map and output duty is PID controlled.
contextHelp.vvt2Enabled: Secondary VVT output. Uses same frequency and control algorithm as primary VVT output.
contextHelp.vvtPWMdir: This is used to invert VVT closed loop PID direction if needed.
contextHelp.vvt2PWMdir: This is used to invert VVT2 closed loop PID direction if needed.
contextHelp.vvtCL0DutyAng: This value is used to bring the VVT cam angle to 0-100 range in closed loop mode by subtracting this value from the raw cam angle reading.
contextHelp.vvt2CL0DutyAng: This value is used to bring the VVT2 cam angle to 0-100 range in closed loop mode by subtracting this value from the raw cam angle reading.
contextHelp.vvtCLMinAng: Safety limit for minimum expected cam angle value. If cam angle gets smaller or equal to this, it triggers VVT error state, closed loop adjustment is disabled and VVT output duty drops to 0%
contextHelp.vvtCLMaxAng: Safety limit for maximum expected cam angle value. If cam angle gets bigger than this, it triggers VVT error state, closed loop adjustment is disabled and VVT output duty drops to 0%
contextHelp.ANGLEFILTER_VVT: Can be used to smooth out cam angle readings if needed. Only supported on specific decoders that have cam angle reading capability
contextHelp.vvtMinClt: Minimum coolant temp to activate VVT
contextHelp.vvtDelay: Time to wait after reaching minimum coolant temp (additional time for oil warmup)
contextHelp.wmiMode:
Simple mode - Output is turned on when preset boost level is reached. 
Proportional Mode - Output PWM is proportionally controlled between two MAP values - MAP Value 1 = PWM:0% / MAP Value 2 = PWM:100% 
Open loop - Output PWM follows 2D map value (RPM vs MAP) Cell value contains desired PWM% [range 0-100%] 
Closed loop - Output PWM follows injector duty cycle with 2D correction map applied (RPM vs MAP). Cell value contains correction value% [nom 100%]
contextHelp.stagedInjSizePri: Size of the primary injectors. The sum of the Pri and Sec injectors values MUST match the value used in the req_fuel calculation
contextHelp.stagedInjSizeSec: Size of the secondary injectors. The sum of the Pri and Sec injectors values MUST match the value used in the req_fuel calculation
contextHelp.resetControl: If set to Serial Command, normally hold the control pin high but pull it low when the 'U' serial command is issued and reset upon receiving more data. The control pin should be connected to the Arduino's reset pin.
contextHelp.resetControlPin: The Arduino pin used to control resets.
contextHelp.rtc_mode: Enables the real time clock for time keeping
contextHelp.onboard_log_file_style: Sdcard datalogger can be Disabled, CSV=Comma separated values, Binary is a Binary format equal to the A comand style current status
contextHelp.onboard_log_file_rate: Rate at wich data is recorded to the logger storage
contextHelp.onboard_log_filenaming: [Overwrite] the file is over written every time the a new log is started, [Date-time] creates a new file in the format YYMMDD-HHMMSS every datalog start, [Seqential] numbers the filenames + 1 on every datalog start
contextHelp.onboard_log_storage: Only [sd-card] as datastorage is implemented at the moment, A FAT16 or FAT32 formatted sd card can be used
contextHelp.onboard_log_trigger_boot: [On boot] the logger is started immediately on boot of the board
contextHelp.onboard_log_trigger_RPM: [RPM] the logger is started when RPM is above the on threshold and stopped below the off threshold
contextHelp.onboard_log_trigger_prot: [engine protection] the logger is started one of the corresponding bits in the engine protection is set
contextHelp.onboard_log_trigger_Vbat: [Battery Voltage] the logger is started when the battery voltage is above the on threshold and stopped below the off threshold
contextHelp.onboard_log_trigger_Epin: [Ext pin [polling]] the logger is running for as long the chosen pin is high and stopped when it is low. When set to [Ext pin [toggle]] the logger is toggled on/off with a pulse on this chosen pin number
contextHelp.onboard_log_tr1_duration: When logging from boot is enabled, this is the duration the log will run for
contextHelp.onboard_log_tr2_thr_on: When the engine RPM is above this threshold the datalogger is started
contextHelp.onboard_log_tr2_thr_off: When the engine RPM is below this threshold the datalogger is stopped
contextHelp.onboard_log_tr3_thr_RPM: When the bits of the RPM engine protection function are set the datalogger is started when no set anymore the logger is stopped
contextHelp.onboard_log_tr3_thr_MAP: When the bits of the MAP engine protection function are set the datalogger is started when no set anymore the logger is stopped
contextHelp.onboard_log_tr3_thr_Oil: When the bits of the Oil engine protection function are set the datalogger is started when no set anymore the logger is stopped
contextHelp.onboard_log_tr3_thr_AFR: When the bits of the AFR engine protection function are set the datalogger is started when no set anymore the logger is stopped
contextHelp.onboard_log_tr4_thr_on: When the measured battery voltage is above this threshold the datalogger is started
contextHelp.onboard_log_tr4_thr_off: When the measured battery voltage is below this threshold the datalogger is stopped
contextHelp.onboard_log_tr5_Epin_pin: The pin to trigger the datalogger start/stop
contextHelp.onboard_log_csv_separator: Choose what character is used for the CSV separator between fields
contextHelp.battVCorMode: The Battery Voltage Correction value from the table below can either be applied on the whole injection Pulse Width value, or only on the Open Time value.
contextHelp.dwellTable: Sets the dwell time in milliseconds based on RPM/load. This can be used to reduce stress/wear on ignition system where long dwell is not needed. And other areas can use longer dwell value if needed for stronger spark. Battery voltage correction is applied for these dwell values.
contextHelp.useDwellMap: In normal operation mode this is set to No and speeduino will use fixed running dwell value. But if different dwell values are required across engine RPM/load range, this can be set to Yes and separate Dwell table defines running dwell value.
contextHelp.tachoMode: The output mode for the tacho pulse. Fixed timing will produce a pulse that is always of the same duration, which works better with mode modern digital tachos. Dwell based output creates a pulse that is matched to the coil/s dwell time. If enabled the tacho pulse duration and timing is same as coil dwell and the number of pulses is same as number of ignition events. This can work better on some styles of tacho but note that the pulse duration might become problem on higher cylinder number engines.
contextHelp.canBMWCluster: Enables CAN broadcasting for BMW E46, E39 and E38 instrument clusters with message ID's 0x316, 0x329 and 0x545
contextHelp.canVAGCluster: Enables CAN broadcasting for VAG instrument clusters with message ID's 0x280 and 0x5A0
contextHelp.boostControlEnable: Set the trigger to enable/disable the closedloop boost controller. When set to: \n 'fixed': if the fuel load exceeds the threshold closedloop boost controller is enbaled.\n 'baro': if the fuel load exceeds the baro the controller is enabled (legacy)
contextHelp.boostDCWhenDisabled: When the closedloop boost controller is disabled by 'enable trigger', this is the Duty cycle set on the boost selenoid. Ususally this is 99% because it keeps the waste gate firmly closed until the threshold and builds boost as fast as possible (no wastegate leak)
contextHelp.boostControlEnableThreshold: When the 'Boost control enable trigger' is set to 'fixed', this value is used as threshold. Usually the value is set just below the wastgate pressure of the used turbo setup. For example 130kpa for a 0.3 bar wastegate actuator. Below this value the ECU has no control over the boost anyway.
